<h2>Service Pages: The Foundation of Med Spa SEO</h2>
<p>A single "Services" page listing all your treatments is not enough. Each treatment needs its own dedicated page. This is the single most impactful change most med spas can make.</p>
<h3>Why Individual Service Pages Win</h3>
<p>Google ranks pages, not websites. A page titled "Botox in Dallas" targets that specific keyword. A page titled "Our Services" targets nothing.</p>
<p>Individual service pages also give you:
- A unique URL to rank for each treatment keyword
- Space for treatment-specific content (600+ words)
- A dedicated landing page for Google Ads
- Structured data (schema markup) for each service
- Internal linking opportunities between related treatments</p>
<h3>The Ideal Service Page Structure</h3>
<p>Every med spa service page should follow this structure:</p>
<p><strong>1. H1 headline with treatment + location</strong>
Example: "Botox in Dallas, TX | [Med Spa Name]"</p>
<p><strong>2. Opening paragraph (60 to 80 words)</strong>
What the treatment is, who it is for, and why patients choose your med spa for it. Include the primary keyword in the first sentence.</p>
<p><strong>3. How it works section (H2)</strong>
Explain the procedure in plain language. Patients want to know what happens during their appointment. Cover preparation, procedure duration, and what to expect.</p>
<p><strong>4. Benefits section (H2)</strong>
List 5 to 8 specific benefits. Use bullet points. Focus on outcomes patients care about: reduced wrinkles, smoother skin, no downtime, natural-looking results.</p>
<p><strong>5. Ideal candidate section (H2)</strong>
Who is a good candidate for this treatment. This helps with <a href="/blog/search-intent-guide/">search intent matching</a> and reduces unqualified inquiries.</p>
<p><strong>6. Before and after gallery (H2)</strong>
Real patient photos with consent. Before-and-after images build trust and keep visitors on the page longer. Both signals help rankings.</p>
<p><strong>7. Pricing or cost range (H2)</strong>
Patients search for pricing. If you do not publish it, they leave your site and find someone who does. A price range ("Botox starts at $12 per unit") is sufficient.</p>
<p><strong>8. FAQ section (H2)</strong>
Answer the 4 to 6 most common questions about the treatment. Use the exact questions patients ask (from Google autocomplete and "People Also Ask"). <a href="/blog/schema-markup-for-blog-posts/">FAQ schema markup</a> can earn rich results in search.</p>
<p><strong>9. Call to action</strong>
A clear booking button or contact form above the fold and at the bottom. Include your phone number for patients who prefer calling.</p>
<h3>Minimum Content Length</h3>
<p>Each service page needs a minimum of 600 words. The top-ranking med spa service pages average 800 to 1,200 words. More content gives Google more context to understand what the page is about and which queries to rank it for.</p>
<p>Do not pad content with fluff. Every sentence should inform, educate, or move the patient closer to booking.</p>
<h2>Local SEO: Ranking in the Map Pack</h2>
<p>The Google Map Pack (the 3-pack of local results with a map) appears for nearly every "near me" and location-based med spa search. Ranking in the Map Pack puts your med spa above all organic results.</p>
<h3>The 3 Factors Google Uses</h3>
<p>Google ranks local results based on 3 factors:</p>
<ol>
<li><strong>Relevance</strong>. How well your profile matches the search query. Detailed service descriptions and accurate categories improve relevance.</li>
<li><strong>Distance</strong>. How close your med spa is to the searcher. You cannot change your location, but you can target nearby neighborhoods in your content.</li>
<li><strong>Prominence</strong>. How well-known your business is online. Reviews, citations, backlinks, and website authority all contribute to prominence.</li>
</ol>
<h3>NAP Consistency</h3>
<p>NAP stands for Name, Address, Phone Number. Your NAP must be identical everywhere it appears online: GBP, website, Yelp, Healthgrades, RealSelf, Facebook, and every other directory.</p>
<p>Inconsistent NAP confuses Google and reduces your local ranking. Use the same format everywhere. If your address is "123 Main St, Suite 200," do not list it as "123 Main Street #200" on another site.</p>
<h3>Build Local Citations</h3>
<p>Citations are mentions of your med spa on other websites. The more consistent citations you have, the stronger your local signals.</p>
<p><strong>Priority directories for med spas:</strong>
- Google Business Profile
- Yelp
- Healthgrades
- RealSelf
- Zocdoc
- Vitals
- Facebook
- Apple Maps
- Bing Places
- YellowPages</p>
<p>Each directory listing should include your NAP, website URL, business hours, and a description of services. <a href="/blog/local-seo-guide/">Local citation building</a> is one of the most reliable ways to improve Map Pack rankings.</p>
