<h2>Reviews: The Ranking Factor You Control</h2>
<p>Google reviews directly influence your Map Pack rankings and your conversion rate. 83% of patients check Google reviews before booking a med spa appointment. The med spas with the most reviews and highest ratings win.</p>
<h3>How Many Reviews You Need</h3>
<p>There is no magic number. But the data is clear: med spas with 50+ Google reviews appear in the Map Pack far more often than those with 10 or fewer. Aim for a consistent flow of new reviews every month.</p>
<p>Review velocity matters more than total count. A med spa that gets 8 new reviews per month outranks one with 200 total reviews but none in the last 3 months. Google values recency.</p>
<h3>How to Get More Reviews</h3>
<p>The best time to ask for a review is right after a positive experience. Build a system around it.</p>
<p><strong>Review generation checklist:</strong>
- [ ] Place a QR code at the front desk linking to your Google review page
- [ ] Send an automated text or email 24 hours after each appointment
- [ ] Train staff to ask satisfied patients for a review before they leave
- [ ] Include a review link in your post-treatment follow-up emails
- [ ] Respond to every review within 24 to 48 hours</p>
<p>The QR code and automated follow-up combination consistently generates the most reviews. Make it as easy as possible. One tap. No login required.</p>
<h3>How to Respond to Reviews</h3>
<p>Respond to every review. Positive and negative. Google has confirmed that review responses are a local ranking signal.</p>
<p><strong>For positive reviews:</strong> Thank the patient by name (if they shared it). Mention the treatment they received. Invite them back.</p>
<p><strong>For negative reviews:</strong> Acknowledge the concern. Apologize for the experience. Offer to resolve it offline. Never argue, get defensive, or share patient details.</p>
<p>Review responses also show prospective patients that you care about the experience. That trust signal influences booking decisions more than most marketing tactics.</p>
<p>For detailed strategies, see our guide on <a href="/blog/get-more-google-reviews-local-business/">getting more Google reviews for local businesses</a>.</p>
<h2>Content Strategy: Blog Posts That Attract Patients</h2>
<p>Med spa blog content serves 2 purposes: ranking for informational keywords and building <a href="/blog/build-topical-authority/">topical authority</a> that strengthens your service pages.</p>
<h3>Content Topics That Work</h3>
<p><strong>Treatment education posts:</strong>
- "What Is Microneedling? Everything You Need to Know"
- "Botox vs. Dysport: Which Is Right for You?"
- "How Long Does Lip Filler Last?"
- "Chemical Peel Recovery: What to Expect Day by Day"</p>
<p><strong>Cost and comparison posts:</strong>
- "How Much Does CoolSculpting Cost in [City]?"
- "Laser Hair Removal vs. Waxing: Permanent Results vs. Temporary Fix"
- "Is PRP Worth It? Results, Costs, and What to Expect"</p>
<p><strong>Seasonal and trend posts:</strong>
- "Spring Skin Prep: 5 Treatments to Book Before Summer"
- "Best Anti-Aging Treatments for Your 30s, 40s, and 50s"
- "New Med Spa Treatments in 2026: What to Know"</p>
<p><strong>Local content:</strong>
- "Best Med Spa in [City]: What to Look For"
- "[City] Med Spa Guide: Treatments, Costs, and What to Expect"</p>
<h3>Publishing Frequency</h3>
<p>The med spas ranking highest on Google publish 8 to 16 blog posts per month. Most med spas publish 0 to 2. That gap is your opportunity.</p>
<p>Consistent publishing builds topical authority. Google sees a med spa that publishes weekly about skincare, injectables, and body treatments as more authoritative than one with a dormant blog.</p>
<p>You do not need to write every post yourself. A <a href="/blog/scale-blog-content-ai/">content automation approach</a> lets you publish at volume without hiring a full content team.</p>
<h3>Content Structure for Rankings</h3>
<p>Every blog post should follow the same <a href="/blog/blog-post-structure-seo/">SEO structure</a>:</p>
<ol>
<li><strong>H1 title</strong> with the target keyword</li>
<li><strong>Opening paragraph</strong> that answers the core question in 2 to 3 sentences</li>
<li><strong>H2 sections</strong> breaking the topic into logical subtopics</li>
<li><strong>Internal links</strong> to relevant service pages and other blog posts</li>
<li><strong>FAQ section</strong> with schema markup</li>
<li><strong>Call to action</strong> for booking or consultation</li>
</ol>
<p>Posts targeting treatment keywords should link to the corresponding service page. A blog post about "Botox recovery timeline" should link to your Botox service page. That <a href="/blog/internal-linking-blog-posts/">internal link</a> passes authority and helps both pages rank.</p>
